WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.956
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:07.335 --> 00:00:08.802
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:11.736 --> 00:00:13.610
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: Thank you.

00:00:13.610 --> 00:00:16.460
SPEAKER 2: So it's been a few
years since we had you in,

00:00:16.460 --> 00:00:18.120
and the last time
you were here you

00:00:18.120 --> 00:00:19.880
were speaking about
"NOPI: The Cookbook."

00:00:19.880 --> 00:00:20.850
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: Yeah.

00:00:20.850 --> 00:00:24.900
SPEAKER 2: And it seems
like quite a change

00:00:24.900 --> 00:00:27.230
or a shift in terms of
a restaurant cookbook

00:00:27.230 --> 00:00:28.037
to this being--

00:00:28.037 --> 00:00:29.245
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: This, yeah.

00:00:29.245 --> 00:00:30.360
SPEAKER 2: --a home cookbook.

00:00:30.360 --> 00:00:31.620
Tell us a little
bit about the shift.

00:00:31.620 --> 00:00:33.300
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: It's like
the two ends of the spectrum

00:00:33.300 --> 00:00:34.300
of Ottolenghi cookbooks.

00:00:34.300 --> 00:00:37.140
So on the one hand you have
"NOPI," and on the other hand,

00:00:37.140 --> 00:00:37.890
you have "Simple."

00:00:37.890 --> 00:00:44.270
And it's a little bit the
story of my personal journey.

00:00:44.270 --> 00:00:46.705
So the books really
don't come in any--

00:00:46.705 --> 00:00:48.360
they're a bit random
in the way they

00:00:48.360 --> 00:00:50.040
come out, because they are--

00:00:50.040 --> 00:00:53.490
the reasons why a certain book
comes out at a certain time

00:00:53.490 --> 00:00:56.430
has a lot to do with
the people that I

00:00:56.430 --> 00:01:01.140
collaborate with on the books
and what we feel like doing.

00:01:01.140 --> 00:01:05.129
And with "NOPI" that
was out two years ago,

00:01:05.129 --> 00:01:08.970
it was Scully, who's
the head chef there, was

00:01:08.970 --> 00:01:12.900
really eager to put
all that creative stuff

00:01:12.900 --> 00:01:16.140
that has gone into the making
of that restaurant into a book.

00:01:16.140 --> 00:01:18.102
And we were starting
writing down recipes.

00:01:18.102 --> 00:01:19.560
And I said to the
publishers, look,

00:01:19.560 --> 00:01:23.020
we've got to do this now,
because this is happening.

00:01:23.020 --> 00:01:24.390
And so that came out.

00:01:24.390 --> 00:01:26.680
And then "Simple,"
which is, like I said,

00:01:26.680 --> 00:01:30.060
the other end of the spectrum,
which is really geared towards

00:01:30.060 --> 00:01:36.750
home cooks and also a much more
comfortable way of cooking with

00:01:36.750 --> 00:01:39.300
ease and simplicity-- and
we can talk more about that

00:01:39.300 --> 00:01:41.130
in a minute--

00:01:41.130 --> 00:01:45.747
came about after I've had
a couple of supplements

00:01:45.747 --> 00:01:46.580
with "The Guardian."

00:01:46.580 --> 00:01:49.140
So "The Guardian" called me.

00:01:49.140 --> 00:01:51.300
I publish recipes in "The
Guardian" every weekend,

00:01:51.300 --> 00:01:54.240
but a few years ago my
editor called me and said,

00:01:54.240 --> 00:01:57.870
I'd like 20 easy recipes for
the spring for a supplement.

00:01:57.870 --> 00:01:59.640
And I went like,
I don't do simple.

00:01:59.640 --> 00:02:00.180
I'm sorry.

00:02:00.180 --> 00:02:00.680
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:00.680 --> 00:02:03.520
And I don't do easy either.

00:02:03.520 --> 00:02:07.170
Because it just seems
so weird to even

00:02:07.170 --> 00:02:08.729
start thinking like that.

00:02:08.729 --> 00:02:11.850
Because I've never
had to convince anyone

00:02:11.850 --> 00:02:15.140
that it's not worth your
while spending all this time

00:02:15.140 --> 00:02:18.540
in the kitchen to get something
as good as what I thought

00:02:18.540 --> 00:02:20.380
I put there.

00:02:20.380 --> 00:02:23.300
But I said, OK,
we'll think about it.

00:02:23.300 --> 00:02:25.500
And I sat down with
my two collaborators

00:02:25.500 --> 00:02:28.770
on the book, Tara
and Esme, who have

00:02:28.770 --> 00:02:31.770
been part of this process
for quite a while.

00:02:31.770 --> 00:02:34.290
And we just started
talking about what

00:02:34.290 --> 00:02:38.440
might be our 20 simple or
easy recipes for the spring.

00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:39.990
There were also
ingredient-- number

00:02:39.990 --> 00:02:42.420
of ingredients was
limited, et cetera.

00:02:42.420 --> 00:02:43.930
And we just had so much fun.

00:02:43.930 --> 00:02:47.940
So we all brought our
little tricks from home--

00:02:47.940 --> 00:02:49.620
things from cans and frozen.

00:02:49.620 --> 00:02:54.930
And Esme, who has been cooking
for many years on boats--

00:02:54.930 --> 00:02:57.360
she was cooking on yachts
for about 10 years,

00:02:57.360 --> 00:02:59.169
she had all these
nifty tricks about--

00:02:59.169 --> 00:03:01.710
obviously, you can't spend a
lot of time and everything needs

00:03:01.710 --> 00:03:03.970
to be very solid,
and well-grounded,

00:03:03.970 --> 00:03:06.480
as you can imagine, on boats--

00:03:06.480 --> 00:03:08.760
had her set of
ideas on what to do.

00:03:08.760 --> 00:03:13.680
And within 20 minutes, we had
20 ideas but really cool things

00:03:13.680 --> 00:03:17.460
that we were very proud
of doing, and it was fun.

00:03:17.460 --> 00:03:22.350
And sometimes, I'm sure
it's applicable to almost

00:03:22.350 --> 00:03:25.440
every field of human
creation, when you've

00:03:25.440 --> 00:03:28.980
got this set of
limitations, it actually

00:03:28.980 --> 00:03:30.310
makes you more creative.

00:03:30.310 --> 00:03:35.000
So it was like, OK, we need
to make it simple in some way.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:38.550
And that's how the
supplements came about,

00:03:38.550 --> 00:03:41.280
and that's how the book
came about as a result

00:03:41.280 --> 00:03:45.270
of those "Guardian" supplements.

00:03:45.270 --> 00:03:47.610
But the other
thing that had also

00:03:47.610 --> 00:03:49.560
happened that led to
this book, or the way

00:03:49.560 --> 00:03:56.070
the book has shaped
up to be this thing,

00:03:56.070 --> 00:03:59.040
was that last year another
cookery writer, Diana Henry,

00:03:59.040 --> 00:04:01.090
came up with a book
called "Simple."

00:04:01.090 --> 00:04:04.510
And I saw that,
and I go, oh, gosh.

00:04:04.510 --> 00:04:05.010
No.

00:04:05.010 --> 00:04:05.760
What do we do now?

00:04:05.760 --> 00:04:08.325
Because she's just
stolen my title.

00:04:08.325 --> 00:04:09.360
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:10.140 --> 00:04:13.710
And it happened to us already
before, really weirdly

00:04:13.710 --> 00:04:18.269
and bizarrely, when
"Plenty" came out, which

00:04:18.269 --> 00:04:21.880
is six years ago, I think, now.

00:04:21.880 --> 00:04:25.350
I published that book and
I got a really angry--

00:04:25.350 --> 00:04:27.720
not really angry but frustrated
email from her, saying,

00:04:27.720 --> 00:04:29.430
"My next book was
going to be 'Plenty--'"

00:04:29.430 --> 00:04:30.630
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:30.630 --> 00:04:33.980
--which is-- it's funny.

00:04:33.980 --> 00:04:37.530
So she had to find a
derivative title with the word

00:04:37.530 --> 00:04:39.840
"plenty" in it, and now I
call this book "Ottolenghi

00:04:39.840 --> 00:04:41.460
Simple" rather than "Simple."

00:04:41.460 --> 00:04:43.020
And I was really
happy to do that,

00:04:43.020 --> 00:04:46.270
because what it made us think
is we sat down and thought,

00:04:46.270 --> 00:04:49.260
what makes "Ottolenghi
Simple" simple?

00:04:49.260 --> 00:04:51.865
So obviously we had
to complicate things.

00:04:51.865 --> 00:04:52.365
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:52.365 --> 00:04:54.030
And so we said--

00:04:54.030 --> 00:04:55.260
SPEAKER 2: So tell us about
the philosophy behind "Simple."

00:04:55.260 --> 00:04:57.593
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: Yeah, so
I'll tell you about the extra

00:04:57.593 --> 00:04:59.880
complication that we added
to the simple notion,

00:04:59.880 --> 00:05:06.180
and that's the coding
system with the S-I-M-P-L-E.

00:05:06.180 --> 00:05:08.640
And essentially what we tried
to do is we started talking

00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:10.470
to people around
us and asked them,

00:05:10.470 --> 00:05:12.960
what is simple cooking for you?

00:05:12.960 --> 00:05:15.379
And we got really
different answers.

00:05:15.379 --> 00:05:16.920
So some would say,
oh, you know, it's

00:05:16.920 --> 00:05:20.150
about coming home and putting
a dish on the table within 20

00:05:20.150 --> 00:05:21.150
minutes or half an hour.

00:05:21.150 --> 00:05:23.670
And some other people said,
I don't want to go shopping.

00:05:23.670 --> 00:05:26.100
I just want to cook it
from things that I really

00:05:26.100 --> 00:05:29.710
have lurking around-- a packet
of rice, a couple of lemons,

00:05:29.710 --> 00:05:34.670
and some garlic, things that
you make from what you've got.

00:05:34.670 --> 00:05:37.800
Others said, I really
want to cook everything

00:05:37.800 --> 00:05:42.244
in advance, so either
for weekend cooking,

00:05:42.244 --> 00:05:44.160
or for weekday cooking
or for weekend cooking.

00:05:44.160 --> 00:05:45.993
I just want to make
sure everything is ready

00:05:45.993 --> 00:05:50.340
and then I just put it
out or put it together

00:05:50.340 --> 00:05:51.370
at the very last minute.

00:05:51.370 --> 00:05:53.100
So there were very
different notions

00:05:53.100 --> 00:05:55.280
of what simple cooking is.

00:05:55.280 --> 00:06:01.410
And, hence, the S-I-M-P-L-E,
and each one is a different

00:06:01.410 --> 00:06:04.740
category of recipes in the book.

00:06:04.740 --> 00:06:08.160
S stands for short--

00:06:08.160 --> 00:06:12.114
short on time, so anything that
would take 20 minutes, half

00:06:12.114 --> 00:06:12.780
an hour to cook.

00:06:12.780 --> 00:06:15.570
The I stands for ingredients--

00:06:15.570 --> 00:06:19.650
10 or less, which, in
my world, 10 or less

00:06:19.650 --> 00:06:20.940
is really the bare minimum.

00:06:20.940 --> 00:06:22.050
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:22.050 --> 00:06:26.940
This is not Jamie
Oliver's "5 Ingredients."

00:06:26.940 --> 00:06:29.481
The M stands for make ahead.

00:06:29.481 --> 00:06:30.980
SPEAKER 2: Make
ahead of time, yeah.

00:06:30.980 --> 00:06:34.440
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: The P stands
for pantry, so we cover that--

00:06:34.440 --> 00:06:39.720
rice, pasta, couscous,
everything that is frozen--

00:06:39.720 --> 00:06:44.047
frozen peas, frozen
corn and things.

00:06:44.047 --> 00:06:45.630
It sounds terrible,
but actually those

00:06:45.630 --> 00:06:48.020
are some of my favorite
dishes in the book.

00:06:48.020 --> 00:06:51.220
The L stands for lazy,
and lazy is those--

00:06:51.220 --> 00:06:53.130
and it's not you being lazy.

00:06:53.130 --> 00:06:56.320
It's just the attitude of
being lazy when you want to be.

00:06:56.320 --> 00:07:00.490
And those are recipes that cook
themselves-- stews and roasts.

00:07:00.490 --> 00:07:02.640
And so you put it there.

00:07:02.640 --> 00:07:03.450
You go read a book.

00:07:03.450 --> 00:07:05.820
You come back and
you've got a meal.

00:07:05.820 --> 00:07:08.880
And the E is an extra
category that we

00:07:08.880 --> 00:07:11.140
added which is called
"Easier Than you Think."

00:07:11.140 --> 00:07:15.580
And that is more about a state
of mind than anything else.

00:07:15.580 --> 00:07:18.420
So for me, one of
the reasons why

00:07:18.420 --> 00:07:20.250
people are a little
bit intimidated

00:07:20.250 --> 00:07:22.680
by certain ways of
cooking is because they've

00:07:22.680 --> 00:07:25.320
gotten into their heads that
they can't cook this thing,

00:07:25.320 --> 00:07:27.210
or they're not bakers, or they--

00:07:27.210 --> 00:07:29.670
those notions.

00:07:29.670 --> 00:07:35.840
And cooking, like many other
things, is 90% psychology.

00:07:35.840 --> 00:07:37.710
And the E is like an ice cream.

00:07:37.710 --> 00:07:39.300
You never thought you were going
to make ice cream if you don't

00:07:39.300 --> 00:07:41.820
have an ice cream maker
sitting on-- churn ice cream,

00:07:41.820 --> 00:07:45.210
or it's a quick bread that
you can do even if you're not

00:07:45.210 --> 00:07:47.230
a baker, or certain desserts.

00:07:47.230 --> 00:07:51.420
It's also things that have
like a complicated French name,

00:07:51.420 --> 00:07:53.107
like a confit or
something like that.

00:07:53.107 --> 00:07:54.690
You think that's
just for restaurants,

00:07:54.690 --> 00:07:55.606
but that's not for me.

00:07:55.606 --> 00:07:57.100
But actually it could be.

00:07:57.100 --> 00:07:59.970
So yeah, that's the system.

00:07:59.970 --> 00:08:03.570
So every recipe in the book
would have at least one

00:08:03.570 --> 00:08:07.290
of those marks but
could have more of them.

00:08:07.290 --> 00:08:10.540
Some recipes are
all six of them.

00:08:10.540 --> 00:08:12.870
SPEAKER 2: So if I
wanted to make something

00:08:12.870 --> 00:08:15.349
in under 30 minutes, I
would look for everything

00:08:15.349 --> 00:08:16.140
with the S symbol--

00:08:16.140 --> 00:08:17.130
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: With
the S on it, yeah.

00:08:17.130 --> 00:08:17.400
SPEAKER 2: --and attempt.

00:08:17.400 --> 00:08:17.820
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: Yeah.

00:08:17.820 --> 00:08:19.470
So that would be--
that's the way.

00:08:19.470 --> 00:08:24.820
It's really about-- and so
we were talking just now.

00:08:24.820 --> 00:08:27.450
I'm doing a podcast
at the moment

00:08:27.450 --> 00:08:28.890
called "Simple Pleasures."

00:08:28.890 --> 00:08:32.130
And the podcast came
about from the same series

00:08:32.130 --> 00:08:35.289
of conversations that we were
having about simple cooking.

00:08:35.289 --> 00:08:38.429
And I wanted to just
expand that a little bit

00:08:38.429 --> 00:08:41.734
into other conversations with
people that either they're

00:08:41.734 --> 00:08:43.150
from food or they're
not from food

00:08:43.150 --> 00:08:45.960
but can say
something about, what

00:08:45.960 --> 00:08:50.760
does it mean to cook or live
simply, or with more ease?

00:08:50.760 --> 00:08:54.930
And so I expanded
this from kitchens

00:08:54.930 --> 00:08:56.010
to other areas of life.

00:08:56.010 --> 00:08:59.760
And I've got people coming on
the podcast and talking to me

00:08:59.760 --> 00:09:02.610
about what they do--
what makes them at ease,

00:09:02.610 --> 00:09:04.470
or what other
aspects of their life

00:09:04.470 --> 00:09:07.530
apart from what
they're famous for.

00:09:07.530 --> 00:09:12.110
They've pared down or
loosened up a little bit.

00:09:12.110 --> 00:09:13.860
And I think it's just
really refreshing

00:09:13.860 --> 00:09:16.050
sometimes to talk about this.

00:09:16.050 --> 00:09:20.040
Because for me, I meet a lot
of cooks, and many of them

00:09:20.040 --> 00:09:22.770
talked about anxiety
when it comes to food.

00:09:22.770 --> 00:09:26.310
And for me, the idea of
mixing cooking with anxiety

00:09:26.310 --> 00:09:29.160
is really counterintuitive,
because cooking

00:09:29.160 --> 00:09:31.740
should be the one thing
that de-stresses, right?

00:09:31.740 --> 00:09:34.250
That's why I got into the
kitchen-- to de-stress.

00:09:34.250 --> 00:09:37.235
And I think this should
be the whole story.

00:09:37.235 --> 00:09:39.360
There shouldn't be anything
beyond the de-stressing

00:09:39.360 --> 00:09:40.290
in the kitchen.

00:09:40.290 --> 00:09:42.600
But because cooking is
also used to impress,

00:09:42.600 --> 00:09:46.320
and people put a lot of pressure
on themselves to impress,

00:09:46.320 --> 00:09:49.290
often it's about reinventing
yourself every time

00:09:49.290 --> 00:09:51.660
you walk into the kitchen,
and that is really stressful.

00:09:51.660 --> 00:09:56.700
I couldn't do it, to create
a meal from a cuisine

00:09:56.700 --> 00:09:58.800
that you haven't even tasted.

00:09:58.800 --> 00:10:01.410
And you want to
do that sometimes,

00:10:01.410 --> 00:10:04.800
but essentially, it really
isn't the way forward.

00:10:04.800 --> 00:10:07.290
The way forward, if you want
to use the kitchen and a tool

00:10:07.290 --> 00:10:13.060
to inject some more
ease, as I said,

00:10:13.060 --> 00:10:21.144
or simplicity, or a sense
of, yeah, simplicity,

00:10:21.144 --> 00:10:22.810
then you actually
want to cook something

00:10:22.810 --> 00:10:24.518
that you have cooked
before, or something

00:10:24.518 --> 00:10:26.290
that is very familiar,
or something that

00:10:26.290 --> 00:10:29.800
is just a second nature to you.

00:10:29.800 --> 00:10:35.560
Nigella, who was on my
podcast, called it competence.

00:10:35.560 --> 00:10:37.810
And she says
competence doesn't seem

00:10:37.810 --> 00:10:39.312
like a-- it's not a sexy word.

00:10:39.312 --> 00:10:41.270
Although when she says
it, of course it's sexy.

00:10:41.270 --> 00:10:42.020
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:42.020 --> 00:10:44.690
But it's not a sexy word.

00:10:44.690 --> 00:10:48.760
But it means that you just do
something over and over again

00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:50.600
and become really good at it.

00:10:50.600 --> 00:10:53.410
And then you get
over all those issues

00:10:53.410 --> 00:10:56.720
that stand in the way of putting
a good meal on the table.

00:10:56.720 --> 00:11:01.000
And I think I personally
prefer to go to someone's house

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:04.360
knowing that I might have
something at that friend's

00:11:04.360 --> 00:11:07.210
house that I've had before,
but it's really good, right?

00:11:07.210 --> 00:11:10.385
I don't care that I've
had it maybe last year.

00:11:10.385 --> 00:11:11.260
It's absolutely fine.

00:11:11.260 --> 00:11:13.410
SPEAKER 2: But I certainly
suffer from that anxiety

00:11:13.410 --> 00:11:16.490
where I don't cook that much.

00:11:16.490 --> 00:11:18.209
So it's a matter
of-- you're right.

00:11:18.209 --> 00:11:19.000
I need to practice.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:21.220
How many times do
you think I'd need

00:11:21.220 --> 00:11:25.992
to cook a dish 'til I put my
own twist to yours, for example?

00:11:25.992 --> 00:11:26.950
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: Yeah.

00:11:26.950 --> 00:11:30.490
So essentially, it depends
on what you choose to cook.

00:11:30.490 --> 00:11:33.880
So for instance,
I've got two recipes

00:11:33.880 --> 00:11:36.970
in the book for baked rice.

00:11:36.970 --> 00:11:40.010
Baked rice is a really
cool way to cook rice.

00:11:40.010 --> 00:11:42.370
You know many people
don't have a rice cooker

00:11:42.370 --> 00:11:44.290
and haven't come from
an Asian culture are

00:11:44.290 --> 00:11:48.430
a little bit intimidated by
cooking rice, because it's

00:11:48.430 --> 00:11:52.050
quite easy to overcook or
to not have enough liquid.

00:11:52.050 --> 00:11:55.810
So you don't want your
rice to be al dente.

00:11:55.810 --> 00:11:58.520
So baked rice is
a really good way.

00:11:58.520 --> 00:12:02.590
You throw a lot of things in a
roasting tray or baking tray,

00:12:02.590 --> 00:12:05.810
and you seal it with foil
and stick it in the oven,

00:12:05.810 --> 00:12:08.580
and you can leave it there
for longer than you think.

00:12:08.580 --> 00:12:10.990
It isn't strictly
necessary and it

00:12:10.990 --> 00:12:13.920
won't really spoil or anything.

00:12:13.920 --> 00:12:16.667
And it's really a good
way to infuse rice

00:12:16.667 --> 00:12:19.000
with lots of flavor, because
you've got a lot of surface

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:20.190
there, so you can put--

00:12:20.190 --> 00:12:24.310
I add mint leaves, or
cinnamon, or garlic,

00:12:24.310 --> 00:12:26.500
and it just spreads
through the rice.

00:12:26.500 --> 00:12:28.750
Essentially, the
cooking liquids turn

00:12:28.750 --> 00:12:32.290
into really aromatic, beautiful
aromatic stock that just

00:12:32.290 --> 00:12:33.880
makes the rice so delicious.

00:12:33.880 --> 00:12:36.160
And then what you choose
to do with that rice

00:12:36.160 --> 00:12:37.036
is really up to you.

00:12:37.036 --> 00:12:38.410
So once you've
mastered this kind

00:12:38.410 --> 00:12:42.730
of very simple technique of
cooking rice by baking it,

00:12:42.730 --> 00:12:43.240
you--

00:12:43.240 --> 00:12:43.480
SPEAKER 2: I add my own--

00:12:43.480 --> 00:12:45.970
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: It's
easy to improvise.

00:12:45.970 --> 00:12:47.650
There is one recipe
here for rice

00:12:47.650 --> 00:12:49.560
that I just cook all
the time at the moment.

00:12:49.560 --> 00:12:53.530
It's the one with the tomatoes,
that actually the version

00:12:53.530 --> 00:12:55.450
of which is served today here.

00:12:55.450 --> 00:12:58.360
But I don't know if they
followed it strictly.

00:12:58.360 --> 00:12:59.746
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:00.245 --> 00:13:03.580
But essentially-- because
when you cook for a big crowd,

00:13:03.580 --> 00:13:04.760
you don't really do that.

00:13:04.760 --> 00:13:08.789
But you take cherry
tomatoes and garlic cloves

00:13:08.789 --> 00:13:10.330
and some shallots,
and you throw them

00:13:10.330 --> 00:13:14.170
in with cinnamon and olive oil,
and you put it in the oven.

00:13:14.170 --> 00:13:16.711
That's one of the lazy
recipes, because you just

00:13:16.711 --> 00:13:19.210
leave it there for 20 minutes
and then those vegetables just

00:13:19.210 --> 00:13:20.800
cook and flavor the oil.

00:13:20.800 --> 00:13:23.090
And then you throw a packet
of rice in and some water

00:13:23.090 --> 00:13:26.200
and you put foil and let
it do its thing again

00:13:26.200 --> 00:13:27.670
for another 25 minutes.

00:13:27.670 --> 00:13:30.340
So it takes time but
essentially very little effort.

00:13:30.340 --> 00:13:35.557
And you get a whole beautiful,
fragrant meal for rice.

00:13:35.557 --> 00:13:36.640
It's got everything there.

00:13:36.640 --> 00:13:37.670
It's got the vegetables.

00:13:37.670 --> 00:13:38.620
It's got the rice.

00:13:38.620 --> 00:13:40.930
You can add something else,
but it's super delicious.

00:13:40.930 --> 00:13:43.630
And I do it every
weekend because I

00:13:43.630 --> 00:13:46.310
know people love it and
it is very, very easy.

00:13:46.310 --> 00:13:50.560
I can go and play with the kids
while this is doing its thing.

