00:15:56.150 --> 00:15:56.980
SPEAKER 2: Well, what's good?

00:15:56.980 --> 00:15:57.240
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: Maybe--

00:15:57.240 --> 00:15:58.180
SPEAKER 2: Let's
shift to what's good.

00:15:58.180 --> 00:15:59.596
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI:
Yeah, maybe it's

00:15:59.596 --> 00:16:03.620
the tahini from Lebanon or
Palestinian or Israeli tahinis.

00:16:03.620 --> 00:16:04.710
They're just better.

00:16:04.710 --> 00:16:06.780
The sesame seeds are
toasted properly,

00:16:06.780 --> 00:16:08.280
so it's nice and
brown and luscious.

00:16:08.280 --> 00:16:11.250
And also there's no grain
in it, so all the husks

00:16:11.250 --> 00:16:15.540
are properly removed, so
it's really, really smooth.

00:16:15.540 --> 00:16:19.290
And for me, the sesame
being really good

00:16:19.290 --> 00:16:24.780
and tahini being really smooth
are what makes a good tahini

00:16:24.780 --> 00:16:25.660
a really good tahini.

00:16:25.660 --> 00:16:28.650
And once you've tried a proper
one or a really good tahini,

00:16:28.650 --> 00:16:30.377
you realize how good it is.

00:16:30.377 --> 00:16:31.460
It's a bit like olive oil.

00:16:31.460 --> 00:16:34.927
There's a whole range from
very good to not that great.

00:16:34.927 --> 00:16:37.010
And I'm not going to mention
countries that have--

00:16:37.010 --> 00:16:38.470
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:38.470 --> 00:16:39.880
--bad olive oil.

00:16:39.880 --> 00:16:43.930
But actually, it isn't
about the country.

00:16:43.930 --> 00:16:47.410
It's about how it's being done.

00:16:47.410 --> 00:16:48.410
So that's a good tahini.

00:16:48.410 --> 00:16:52.050
