It's Gnocchi alla Romana.

00:21:33.930 --> 00:21:34.652
SPEAKER 2: Mm.

00:21:34.652 --> 00:21:36.360
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: It's
Semollina gnocchi.

00:21:36.360 --> 00:21:39.120
It's not gnocchi from potato
that most people might know,

00:21:39.120 --> 00:21:40.740
but it's made with semolina.

00:21:40.740 --> 00:21:45.720
And my grandmother, who was
Italian, used to make that.

00:21:45.720 --> 00:21:49.140
And again, some people who
grew up in this country

00:21:49.140 --> 00:21:52.650
have a really negative
association with semolina

00:21:52.650 --> 00:21:55.320
because it's been served
in some schools, I hear.

00:21:57.990 --> 00:22:02.670
It was part of the
not-so-loved repertoire

00:22:02.670 --> 00:22:04.260
of school canteens
in this country,

00:22:04.260 --> 00:22:05.970
but luckily I was spared that.

00:22:05.970 --> 00:22:08.970
I arrived late enough to
not have to go through this.

00:22:08.970 --> 00:22:11.550
But semolina is a
great ingredient.

00:22:11.550 --> 00:22:13.560
It absorbs flavors.

00:22:13.560 --> 00:22:16.240
It's really very
smooth and beautiful.

00:22:16.240 --> 00:22:20.190
In Indian cooking, you find
great ways with semolina.

00:22:20.190 --> 00:22:22.930
And so, essentially,
the semolina

00:22:22.930 --> 00:22:25.260
is cooked with Parmesan,
and butter, and some nutmeg,

00:22:25.260 --> 00:22:28.200
and then made into
little circles.

00:22:28.200 --> 00:22:32.610
And those are put under the
grill with some more cheese.

00:22:32.610 --> 00:22:34.680
You don't really
have to say much more

00:22:34.680 --> 00:22:36.230
than that to make you--

00:22:36.230 --> 00:22:37.920
SPEAKER 2: Yes, I'm
getting very hungry.

00:22:37.920 --> 00:22:41.550
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: So that's
another favorite recipe.

