social media accounts,

00:23:07.215 --> 00:23:10.802
and you post lots of pictures
from your test kitchen.

00:23:10.802 --> 00:23:11.760
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: Yeah.

00:23:11.760 --> 00:23:13.770
SPEAKER 2: So at
Google, obviously, we're

00:23:13.770 --> 00:23:15.360
all about the innovation.

00:23:15.360 --> 00:23:19.290
I want to understand how you
go about developing recipes,

00:23:19.290 --> 00:23:21.512
because you basically do
it as a full-time job.

00:23:21.512 --> 00:23:22.470
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: Yeah.

00:23:22.470 --> 00:23:22.969
I am.

00:23:22.969 --> 00:23:26.850
Really, I develop recipes
as a full-time job.

00:23:26.850 --> 00:23:28.790
Well, that's how I feel
most of my time now.

00:23:28.790 --> 00:23:32.530
I go to the restaurants a
lot, too, and try the recipes.

00:23:32.530 --> 00:23:35.290
But I don't cook
in the restaurants.

00:23:39.540 --> 00:23:43.720
My way of developing recipes
has really evolved over time.

00:23:43.720 --> 00:23:46.530
So when I started
testing recipes,

00:23:46.530 --> 00:23:48.640
I used to do it all
from my kitchen at home.

00:23:48.640 --> 00:23:51.690
I used to live in West London,
and I had a small kitchen.

00:23:51.690 --> 00:23:55.710
Up until the book, "Plenty," I
tested every recipe by myself

00:23:55.710 --> 00:23:56.536
at home.

00:23:56.536 --> 00:23:58.410
I used to take my car,
go to the supermarket,

00:23:58.410 --> 00:24:01.830
buy the ingredients, cook, write
the recipe, do the washing up.

00:24:01.830 --> 00:24:06.450
And it was a very inefficient
way of producing recipes.

00:24:06.450 --> 00:24:09.720
But since I only needed to
come up with one recipe a week,

00:24:09.720 --> 00:24:12.570
it was kind of doable.

00:24:12.570 --> 00:24:14.860
But also, the other
problem was that I

00:24:14.860 --> 00:24:19.270
found it really difficult
to get inspired in this way.

00:24:19.270 --> 00:24:22.170
So I would sit with things
and have conversations.

00:24:22.170 --> 00:24:27.630
But really, it was kind of
a lonesome way of working.

00:24:27.630 --> 00:24:30.590
And about 10 years ago, we
started the test kitchen,

00:24:30.590 --> 00:24:33.530
which you're talking about,
which it's not a very--

00:24:33.530 --> 00:24:37.020
if you come there, it's not
a very glamorous environment.

00:24:37.020 --> 00:24:40.980
It's not a Google
head office, but we

00:24:40.980 --> 00:24:45.780
made it really look like
anyone's kitchen in the sense

00:24:45.780 --> 00:24:49.270
that it's a very
low tech kitchen.

00:24:49.270 --> 00:24:50.970
The philosophy behind
that is because I

00:24:50.970 --> 00:24:52.720
don't want to create
something that people

00:24:52.720 --> 00:24:53.890
won't recreate at home.

00:24:53.890 --> 00:24:54.120
SPEAKER 2: Right.

00:24:54.120 --> 00:24:55.620
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI:
So the ingredients

00:24:55.620 --> 00:24:57.710
come from just
ordinary supermarkets.

00:24:57.710 --> 00:25:02.407
And the equipment
is basic equipment.

00:25:02.407 --> 00:25:04.365
And I know a lot of people
have fancy equipment

00:25:04.365 --> 00:25:05.490
at home, but not everybody.

00:25:05.490 --> 00:25:08.610
And I want to know what is
the basic result that people

00:25:08.610 --> 00:25:10.050
would get when I try something.

00:25:10.050 --> 00:25:12.420
That was the idea
behind the test kitchen.

00:25:12.420 --> 00:25:16.140
And I've got a team now
of about three people

00:25:16.140 --> 00:25:19.110
and sometimes more, because
chefs come from the restaurants

00:25:19.110 --> 00:25:21.150
to try their recipes there, too.

00:25:21.150 --> 00:25:24.870
And it's become a great,
creative hub, because people--

00:25:24.870 --> 00:25:28.380
so I've got my team that
develop recipes for books

00:25:28.380 --> 00:25:30.172
and other publications.

00:25:30.172 --> 00:25:32.130
I've got the chefs coming
from the restaurants.

00:25:32.130 --> 00:25:35.410
And the conversations are just
really, really interesting.

00:25:35.410 --> 00:25:39.090
So if something comes
up in one environment,

00:25:39.090 --> 00:25:40.770
it's completely
relevant immediately

00:25:40.770 --> 00:25:42.186
to the other
environment but needs

00:25:42.186 --> 00:25:44.880
to be changed and evolved.

00:25:44.880 --> 00:25:47.820
Like, for instance,
Rovi is a restaurant

00:25:47.820 --> 00:25:50.550
that I opened a few
months ago in Fitzrovia,

00:25:50.550 --> 00:25:52.800
actually not that far from here.

00:25:52.800 --> 00:25:54.840
SPEAKER 2: Which is
great, by the way.

00:25:54.840 --> 00:25:56.020
We'll get onto that.

00:25:56.020 --> 00:25:59.520
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: And we did a
lot of pickling and preserving

00:25:59.520 --> 00:26:01.130
for that.

00:26:01.130 --> 00:26:03.630
Because we were working on
recipes for the restaurant way

00:26:03.630 --> 00:26:04.570
before it opened.

00:26:04.570 --> 00:26:07.250
And the notion of seasonality
was not so clear at that point,

00:26:07.250 --> 00:26:09.750
because we didn't know whether
we were going to open in June

00:26:09.750 --> 00:26:10.950
or whether it was
going to be September,

00:26:10.950 --> 00:26:12.060
and things really change.

00:26:12.060 --> 00:26:14.625
So we pickled quite a lot
of stuff and fermented

00:26:14.625 --> 00:26:16.590
and made sure that we--

00:26:16.590 --> 00:26:19.890
the restaurant is focused on a
grill on which we grill mostly

00:26:19.890 --> 00:26:22.680
vegetables but also
some meat and fish.

00:26:22.680 --> 00:26:26.580
And we wanted to get
those really enticing,

00:26:26.580 --> 00:26:27.490
strong flavors.

00:26:27.490 --> 00:26:29.966
But like I said,
we didn't really

00:26:29.966 --> 00:26:31.590
know exactly when it
was going to open,

00:26:31.590 --> 00:26:33.750
so we had to
preserve and ferment.

00:26:35.820 --> 00:26:40.620
For home cooks, that's quite a
big investment for the future,

00:26:40.620 --> 00:26:42.900
because it takes days
and weeks for things

00:26:42.900 --> 00:26:44.170
to kind of come to their own.

00:26:44.170 --> 00:26:47.340
And so we tested
little shortcuts.

00:26:50.130 --> 00:26:52.020
We've got a Chilean
tomato ferment, which

00:26:52.020 --> 00:26:54.465
is one of my favorite,
and we served it

00:26:54.465 --> 00:26:58.710
with mint as a condiment to
many of the dishes in Rovi.

00:26:58.710 --> 00:27:00.900
We took certain shortcuts.

00:27:00.900 --> 00:27:03.390
Often, we would use--

00:27:03.390 --> 00:27:06.030
you add a little bit of vinegar
and a little bit of sugar, not

00:27:06.030 --> 00:27:08.286
a lot, but just a tiny
bit to get it started.

00:27:08.286 --> 00:27:09.660
And then you leave
it for one day

00:27:09.660 --> 00:27:12.210
or not as long as
that, et cetera.

00:27:12.210 --> 00:27:14.880
So those are conversations
that we constantly have.

00:27:14.880 --> 00:27:16.740
So everybody tries
recipes, and we all

00:27:16.740 --> 00:27:21.330
get together when it's time to
taste and taste and comment.

00:27:21.330 --> 00:27:24.000
Very meticulous notes
are being taken down.

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:29.220
Because for me, recipes,
they have to work.

00:27:29.220 --> 00:27:34.980
I know it sounds really
like it's common sense,

00:27:34.980 --> 00:27:40.290
but I know it's not, because
some recipes don't work.

00:27:40.290 --> 00:27:43.470
We test it a lot.

00:27:43.470 --> 00:27:46.890
Once that's done, there is
a woman who lives in Wales

00:27:46.890 --> 00:27:52.500
and has got a few kids, and a
husband, and extended family.

00:27:52.500 --> 00:27:55.000
And she tests the
recipes on her family.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:28:00.170
Only once that comes back
to me with a completely set

00:28:00.170 --> 00:28:06.335
of comments that are
satisfying, the recipe

00:28:06.335 --> 00:28:07.380
is released to the world.

00:28:07.380 --> 00:28:11.060
So it's a very long process
with various stages.

00:28:11.060 --> 00:28:15.010
SPEAKER 2: Sounds like the
Google hiring process almost.

00:28:15.010 --> 00:28:18.200
How many make the cut?

00:28:18.200 --> 00:28:20.790
2 out of 10 recipes
that make the cut?

00:28:22.282 --> 00:28:24.740
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: When they
get to her, most of them make--

00:28:28.070 --> 00:28:30.290
I would never send something
that I'm not really

00:28:30.290 --> 00:28:31.154
100% happy with.

00:28:31.154 --> 00:28:31.820
SPEAKER 2: Yeah.

00:28:31.820 --> 00:28:33.903
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: And I
learned from my experience

00:28:33.903 --> 00:28:38.500
that normally, if I have some
doubts, then she confirms them.

00:28:38.500 --> 00:28:42.530
Claudine, who is my
recipe tester in Wales,

00:28:42.530 --> 00:28:44.280
she cooked every dish
I've ever published.

00:28:44.280 --> 00:28:45.910
It's 1,000 recipes now.

00:28:45.910 --> 00:28:50.030
She really knows what the
level is and the expectations.

00:28:50.030 --> 00:28:55.730
And she has very honest
people around her also

00:28:55.730 --> 00:28:57.290
confirming what she thinks.

00:28:57.290 --> 00:28:59.250
So normally they come fine.

00:28:59.250 --> 00:29:02.870
But I have a way of
reading what she says.

00:29:02.870 --> 00:29:05.750
I do want the truth, you know?

00:29:05.750 --> 00:29:08.764
When it's excellent, I loved
it, there's no problem.

00:29:08.764 --> 00:29:10.055
But sometimes she writes, nice.

00:29:10.055 --> 00:29:11.774
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:13.180 --> 00:29:15.200
SPEAKER 2: And she's
English, so nice is--

00:29:15.200 --> 00:29:16.500
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: She's
half French, half English.

00:29:16.500 --> 00:29:17.083
SPEAKER 2: OK.

00:29:17.083 --> 00:29:20.600
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI:
But nice is kind of--

00:29:20.600 --> 00:29:23.750
so if I had a tiny bit of
doubt about that recipe when

00:29:23.750 --> 00:29:25.840
it went to her and it
came back with a nice,

00:29:25.840 --> 00:29:31.070
then we take it back, and try
it again, and put a big question

00:29:31.070 --> 00:29:33.284
mark around it and ask,
do we really love it?

00:29:33.284 --> 00:29:33.950
SPEAKER 2: Yeah.

00:29:33.950 --> 00:29:34.850
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI:
Because you really

00:29:34.850 --> 00:29:36.641
need to love the recipes
that go out there,

00:29:36.641 --> 00:29:38.690
because people cook them.

00:29:38.690 --> 00:29:41.840
They go buy the ingredients,
feed their friends and family.

00:29:41.840 --> 00:29:44.270
You really want them to
be pretty spectacular,

00:29:44.270 --> 00:29:46.547
because otherwise, why?

00:29:46.547 --> 00:29:48.380
SPEAKER 2: Well, I'll
ask one more question,

00:29:48.380 --> 00:29:51.620
but I would ask Googlers to
have your questions ready.

00:29:51.620 --> 00:29:54.980
There's a microphone
waiting there.

00:29:54.980 --> 00:29:57.770
My last question is going
to be about food trends.

00:29:57.770 --> 00:30:02.212
So it feels like veganism is
a really big thing right now.

00:30:02.212 --> 00:30:03.170
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: Yeah.

00:30:03.170 --> 00:30:07.640
SPEAKER 2: You've been an early
supporter, I would say, I mean,

00:30:07.640 --> 00:30:09.320
with "Plenty", "Plenty More."

00:30:09.320 --> 00:30:11.930
You've been flying the plant
flag for a very long time now.

00:30:11.930 --> 00:30:12.410
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: Yeah.

00:30:12.410 --> 00:30:14.410
SPEAKER 2: So do you
think it's going to last?

00:30:14.410 --> 00:30:16.912
And what are your thoughts
about trends in general?

00:30:16.912 --> 00:30:17.870
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: Yeah.

00:30:17.870 --> 00:30:23.270
So for me, the interest in
vegetarian and vegan food

00:30:23.270 --> 00:30:27.650
has always been a result of
not so much of an agenda,

00:30:27.650 --> 00:30:32.330
but just because I think there
is just so much there that

00:30:32.330 --> 00:30:34.140
could be enjoyed.

00:30:34.140 --> 00:30:39.800
And so the idea of turning
a non-vegan recipe vegan

00:30:39.800 --> 00:30:41.320
is not something
that I enjoy doing.

00:30:41.320 --> 00:30:46.130
So vegan meat, or vegan
risotto, or anything

00:30:46.130 --> 00:30:49.089
that even just feels like
you're adapting something

00:30:49.089 --> 00:30:50.630
is not something
that I do naturally.

00:30:50.630 --> 00:30:54.500
Because the culture
that I come from,

00:30:54.500 --> 00:30:56.540
or the general Middle
Eastern food culture,

00:30:56.540 --> 00:30:59.330
has a lot of recipes that
are just naturally vegan.

00:30:59.330 --> 00:31:02.010
And in other parts of the
world, that's also the case.

00:31:02.010 --> 00:31:06.500
So I think those are
the good vegan dishes.

00:31:06.500 --> 00:31:08.142
I didn't really
love tofu until I

00:31:08.142 --> 00:31:10.100
went traveling in Southeast
Asia and understood

00:31:10.100 --> 00:31:12.830
what to do with tofu.

00:31:12.830 --> 00:31:16.280
It took a while for
me to warm up to tofu

00:31:16.280 --> 00:31:18.410
and see how well it
should be prepared.

00:31:18.410 --> 00:31:20.420
Once I've seen it, I
realized that tofu is not

00:31:20.420 --> 00:31:23.280
a substitute to meat by any
stretch of the imagination.

00:31:23.280 --> 00:31:28.550
It's a real, proper foodstuff
in China, and Malaysia,

00:31:28.550 --> 00:31:32.240
and Singapore, and other
places in Southeast Asia.

00:31:32.240 --> 00:31:34.430
And it's fantastic,
but you really

00:31:34.430 --> 00:31:36.180
need to know what
you're doing with it.

00:31:36.180 --> 00:31:38.970
So I think veganism is great.

00:31:38.970 --> 00:31:42.230
I think there will be more
people having a vegan diet.

00:31:42.230 --> 00:31:45.830
But I think the
strict vegan diet

00:31:45.830 --> 00:31:52.115
and the strict kind
of vegan way of life,

00:31:52.115 --> 00:31:56.030
that I didn't really enjoy in
its earliest incarnation, which

00:31:56.030 --> 00:31:59.450
was kind of about, like
I said, translating

00:31:59.450 --> 00:32:01.840
other foods into
the vegan language,

00:32:01.840 --> 00:32:05.017
is not something that I think
will stay for a very long time.

00:32:05.017 --> 00:32:07.100
But I think what will
become more and more evident

00:32:07.100 --> 00:32:09.350
is that people want to eat
more and more vegan dishes

00:32:09.350 --> 00:32:10.430
but not strictly vegan.

00:32:10.430 --> 00:32:13.130
And that's what you see
people say quite a lot.

00:32:13.130 --> 00:32:16.520
I've talked quite a lot
about flexitarianism.

00:32:16.520 --> 00:32:17.870
It's a word that people use.

00:32:20.430 --> 00:32:26.010
It sounds a bit like something
you'd put as a headline,

00:32:26.010 --> 00:32:28.830
but it stands for something
much deeper than that.

00:32:28.830 --> 00:32:31.220
It's an understanding
that you need

00:32:31.220 --> 00:32:33.560
to change your way
of eating, but you

00:32:33.560 --> 00:32:35.030
need to be also
practical about it,

00:32:35.030 --> 00:32:36.920
that there's human
nature, that we're humans,

00:32:36.920 --> 00:32:40.380
that we have certain
inclinations, that we

00:32:40.380 --> 00:32:43.000
make certain sacrifices.

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:46.865
So I think that would be the
way we see veganism transforming

00:32:46.865 --> 00:32:52.384
itself, reinventing itself
going into the future.

00:32:52.384 --> 00:32:54.050
SPEAKER 2: And also
of plants just being

00:32:54.050 --> 00:32:58.715
celebrated, like in Rovi, the
things that you do with corn,

00:32:58.715 --> 00:32:59.580
for example.

00:32:59.580 --> 00:33:02.080
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: Yeah,
with corn, or with celeriac,

00:33:02.080 --> 00:33:05.170
or with cauliflower,
or with courgettes.

00:33:05.170 --> 00:33:06.820
Like what I said about lemon--

00:33:06.820 --> 00:33:09.850
that I'm just feeling like
I'm scraping the surface--

00:33:09.850 --> 00:33:11.750
is true about other vegetables.

00:33:11.750 --> 00:33:13.720
And I think vegetables
also have more potential

00:33:13.720 --> 00:33:17.175
to do interesting things
with them than meat and fish,

00:33:17.175 --> 00:33:19.300
because meat and fish are
really great as they are.

00:33:19.300 --> 00:33:21.400
You put a bit of oil and
salt and you grill it,

00:33:21.400 --> 00:33:22.858
and you've got
something delicious.

00:33:22.858 --> 00:33:25.540
But vegetables, it
takes a little bit more.

00:33:25.540 --> 00:33:29.330
But once you start, you
get way more flavor.

00:33:29.330 --> 00:33:31.060
And the techniques
of cooking are

00:33:31.060 --> 00:33:35.692
much more diverse in "Plenty
More" which is an older book

00:33:35.692 --> 00:33:36.400
that I published.

00:33:36.400 --> 00:33:39.370
It was all about how
cooking techniques really

00:33:39.370 --> 00:33:44.740
create very different results
with the same vegetables.

00:33:44.740 --> 00:33:49.020
SPEAKER 2: With that, let's
take some audience questions.

00:33:49.020 --> 00:33:50.220
Don't be shy.

00:33:50.220 --> 00:33:52.140
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: Google
people cannot be shy.

00:33:52.140 --> 00:33:53.280
SPEAKER 2: Yes, come on.

00:33:53.280 --> 00:33:55.196
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: That
is not possible, is it?

00:33:58.200 --> 00:33:59.170
AUDIENCE: Hi, there.

00:33:59.170 --> 00:34:00.460
Thanks for joining us today.

00:34:00.460 --> 00:34:03.750
My question is, what is
your take on sustainability.

00:34:03.750 --> 00:34:07.080
Specifically, does things
like locally sourced, produced

00:34:07.080 --> 00:34:08.920
or organic materials--

00:34:08.920 --> 00:34:12.889
how much does that factor into
the recipes you come up with?

00:34:12.889 --> 00:34:15.540
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: It has become
increasingly more relevant

00:34:15.540 --> 00:34:17.110
to me over the years.

00:34:17.110 --> 00:34:19.889
I think it's definitely
not been high on my agenda

00:34:19.889 --> 00:34:25.400
when I started writing cookbooks
and cooking in general.

00:34:25.400 --> 00:34:27.750
But like many other
people, I've come

00:34:27.750 --> 00:34:31.469
to realize how important
it is to keep this in mind.

00:34:31.469 --> 00:34:34.260
And again, the way I
spoke about veganism,

00:34:34.260 --> 00:34:38.469
I feel a little bit the
same about sustainability.

00:34:38.469 --> 00:34:40.710
You need to be careful
how you apply it,

00:34:40.710 --> 00:34:45.690
because there is a tendency
to look at things at extremes

00:34:45.690 --> 00:34:47.280
and black and white.

00:34:47.280 --> 00:34:49.980
So trading in spices
has been something

00:34:49.980 --> 00:34:52.590
that has been going on for a
very long time, for millennia,

00:34:52.590 --> 00:34:54.409
and we'll keep on doing.

00:34:54.409 --> 00:34:57.480
And I think it's a good thing.

00:34:57.480 --> 00:35:00.012
Importing water
from Fiji has not

00:35:00.012 --> 00:35:01.470
happened for a very
long time and I

00:35:01.470 --> 00:35:02.890
think is not a good thing.

00:35:02.890 --> 00:35:05.410
And I think, in
between those two,

00:35:05.410 --> 00:35:07.170
there's a whole
range of behaviors

00:35:07.170 --> 00:35:08.670
that we need to kind of look at.

00:35:08.670 --> 00:35:10.620
And it's becoming
more and more evident

00:35:10.620 --> 00:35:18.510
that we need to do much less
on the non-sustainable level

00:35:18.510 --> 00:35:19.240
than we do.

00:35:19.240 --> 00:35:21.790
But I'm being very
pragmatic about it.

00:35:21.790 --> 00:35:25.520
One of the things that we're
doing a lot at Rovi, but also

00:35:25.520 --> 00:35:28.650
in the other restaurants,
is working with farmers

00:35:28.650 --> 00:35:32.790
from the area
southeast of England.

00:35:32.790 --> 00:35:35.260
And the partnerships
are really incredible.

00:35:35.260 --> 00:35:38.820
So things like shiso
leaves, which are really

00:35:38.820 --> 00:35:43.620
kind of Japanese,
are grown in Dorset,

00:35:43.620 --> 00:35:46.300
and we get them
within a few hours.

00:35:46.300 --> 00:35:50.850
And so it's just really
beneficial, and useful,

00:35:50.850 --> 00:35:52.080
and good to think that way.

00:35:52.080 --> 00:35:55.830
Because you constantly discover
things that are possible that

00:35:55.830 --> 00:35:56.550
you haven't.

00:35:56.550 --> 00:36:01.250
But as far as I can tell,
coffee will never come from UK.

00:36:01.250 --> 00:36:02.600
SPEAKER 2: I hope not.

00:36:02.600 --> 00:36:04.350
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI:
But we will still

00:36:04.350 --> 00:36:09.030
carry on enjoying coffees, but
hopefully not in paper cups

00:36:09.030 --> 00:36:12.220
but in glass cups that we can
bring with us to the coffee

00:36:12.220 --> 00:36:14.559
shop.

00:36:14.559 --> 00:36:15.100
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:36:15.100 --> 00:36:16.650
Can I become a recipe tester?

00:36:16.650 --> 00:36:17.590
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:18.090 --> 00:36:22.250
Number two, you
mentioned a family.

00:36:22.250 --> 00:36:27.980
How do you create a sense of
fun, creativity, curiosity

00:36:27.980 --> 00:36:30.500
at home when it comes
to food and cooking?

00:36:30.500 --> 00:36:33.290
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: Yeah,
it's really difficult.

00:36:33.290 --> 00:36:35.270
I've got two boys
that are young.

00:36:35.270 --> 00:36:37.130
They're three years
old and five years old.

00:36:44.720 --> 00:36:47.810
Had you asked me this question
before I had children,

00:36:47.810 --> 00:36:50.840
I had this kind of ideal notion
that I'd just put everything

00:36:50.840 --> 00:36:52.550
on the table and
let them experience.

00:36:52.550 --> 00:36:55.340
And they'll eat what you
eat and all the rest.

00:36:55.340 --> 00:36:57.810
It doesn't really
work like that.

00:36:57.810 --> 00:37:03.200
So the new version of this
theory, the slightly more

00:37:03.200 --> 00:37:08.030
realistic version of
this theory is that, yes,

00:37:08.030 --> 00:37:10.850
I do adapt things
for my children.

00:37:10.850 --> 00:37:13.290
Like any other
child that I know,

00:37:13.290 --> 00:37:16.520
their first [INAUDIBLE]
these ages, I mean,

00:37:16.520 --> 00:37:20.600
is a bowl of pasta, pasta
with tomato sauce and cheese.

00:37:20.600 --> 00:37:22.700
And I'd give them
that all the time.

00:37:22.700 --> 00:37:24.860
I put other things around,
and we eat other things,

00:37:24.860 --> 00:37:26.510
and we get them excited.

00:37:26.510 --> 00:37:30.800
But I think showing
them what's going on

00:37:30.800 --> 00:37:32.000
is really, really useful.

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:34.010
Because children are
just naturally curious,

00:37:34.010 --> 00:37:35.670
I mean, way more
curious than adults.

00:37:39.170 --> 00:37:40.692
If you're going to
pickle something,

00:37:40.692 --> 00:37:42.150
they will just ask
lots of question

00:37:42.150 --> 00:37:45.020
before they even think it's
something that they will eat.

00:37:45.020 --> 00:37:51.320
So just opening a kind of
window to the way things are

00:37:51.320 --> 00:37:52.379
is really useful.

00:37:52.379 --> 00:37:54.170
And it doesn't mean
you need to cook a lot.

00:37:54.170 --> 00:37:56.930
It just means that when you
cook, you just expose it.

00:37:56.930 --> 00:38:00.860
Or even just talking about
this or being interested,

00:38:00.860 --> 00:38:03.230
I think that is the
first step to get

00:38:03.230 --> 00:38:06.080
kids involved in this world.

00:38:10.700 --> 00:38:13.130
It shows how middle
class we are,

00:38:13.130 --> 00:38:16.560
but Max, my oldest son came
back from school last year

00:38:16.560 --> 00:38:18.770
and said to me, oh, I
know how to make sushi.

00:38:18.770 --> 00:38:20.390
So they were rolling
sushi at school.

00:38:20.390 --> 00:38:21.172
I said, really?

00:38:21.172 --> 00:38:22.500
That's interesting.

00:38:22.500 --> 00:38:24.320
I don't know how to make sushi.

00:38:24.320 --> 00:38:28.640
And I think he was really
proud of being able to be there

00:38:28.640 --> 00:38:29.410
at that moment.

00:38:32.450 --> 00:38:35.480
You can do all sorts
of things like that.

00:38:35.480 --> 00:38:36.450
Give them a little job.

00:38:36.450 --> 00:38:37.220
Let them do it.

00:38:37.220 --> 00:38:39.350
You might not even cook
that thing that they did.

00:38:39.350 --> 00:38:41.420
But it's just getting
them involved, I think,

00:38:41.420 --> 00:38:43.040
is really, really important.

00:38:47.159 --> 00:38:49.200
AUDIENCE: Do you ever
experience the chef version

00:38:49.200 --> 00:38:50.520
of writer's block?

00:38:50.520 --> 00:38:51.740
And how do you overcome it?

00:38:51.740 --> 00:38:52.770
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: Yeah.

00:38:52.770 --> 00:38:55.770
So I do and I did.

00:38:55.770 --> 00:38:57.300
I did more, but now--

00:38:57.300 --> 00:38:59.460
so this goes back
to the test kitchen,

00:38:59.460 --> 00:39:01.590
which is I don't
think I actually

00:39:01.590 --> 00:39:05.010
finished developing
this idea about how

00:39:05.010 --> 00:39:07.110
the creative process happens.

00:39:07.110 --> 00:39:09.720
I stopped at how strict
we are at testing recipes,

00:39:09.720 --> 00:39:12.240
but I didn't really talk
about the creative process.

00:39:12.240 --> 00:39:15.780
And this is really interesting,
because, like I said,

00:39:15.780 --> 00:39:17.670
when I stopped
working singularly

00:39:17.670 --> 00:39:19.750
and I started
working in a group,

00:39:19.750 --> 00:39:22.390
I found that it's really
helpful for everybody.

00:39:22.390 --> 00:39:24.280
It's very helpful for
me, that's for sure.

00:39:24.280 --> 00:39:29.280
Because every person brings
their own story, history,

00:39:29.280 --> 00:39:32.100
palette to the conversation,
which is great.

00:39:32.100 --> 00:39:34.530
But it's also what
happens when you

00:39:34.530 --> 00:39:37.680
talk about an idea in a
group and how it evolves.

00:39:37.680 --> 00:39:41.700
So often we go, oh, no,
it's asparagus season again.

00:39:41.700 --> 00:39:44.400
It's the dreaded thing,
because in Britain, we

00:39:44.400 --> 00:39:47.250
don't have a lot of things
that are really seasonal

00:39:47.250 --> 00:39:50.310
and really off the plate,
and asparagus is one of them.

00:39:50.310 --> 00:39:51.990
And gooseberries is another one.

00:39:51.990 --> 00:39:54.500
But there's like, how many
columns about asparagus

00:39:54.500 --> 00:39:56.690
can you write?

00:39:56.690 --> 00:40:00.660
But actually, when you sit
down with three or four people

00:40:00.660 --> 00:40:04.890
and you talk about
columns, it's incredible

00:40:04.890 --> 00:40:09.810
how much comes through those
particular conversations,

00:40:09.810 --> 00:40:12.810
much more than you'd think would
come out of you if you haven't

00:40:12.810 --> 00:40:13.830
had those people around.

00:40:13.830 --> 00:40:16.385
So one person's idea
sparks an idea in your mind

00:40:16.385 --> 00:40:17.760
that you didn't
really even have.

00:40:17.760 --> 00:40:23.190
And you develop it into
something completely different.

00:40:23.190 --> 00:40:25.410
Jeremy Lee, who is a
chef that I really like,

00:40:25.410 --> 00:40:29.370
rolls his asparagus in
phyllo and just sprinkles it

00:40:29.370 --> 00:40:31.260
with Parmesan and
fries it or bakes it.

00:40:31.260 --> 00:40:32.790
It's a really great dish.

00:40:32.790 --> 00:40:35.850
And I just had that
in my mind when

00:40:35.850 --> 00:40:38.400
we had the latest asparagus
discussion, which was probably

00:40:38.400 --> 00:40:41.070
in January or something.

00:40:41.070 --> 00:40:44.550
And that idea of rolling
the asparagus in something

00:40:44.550 --> 00:40:48.070
could completely take you to a
completely different direction.

00:40:48.070 --> 00:40:50.340
It's an image more
than anything else.

00:40:50.340 --> 00:40:53.160
But it's something that
you can just use or take.

00:40:53.160 --> 00:40:55.470
You can coat it
with something which

00:40:55.470 --> 00:40:57.420
isn't a pastry or anything.

00:40:57.420 --> 00:41:00.030
So those conversations
are really, really useful

00:41:00.030 --> 00:41:00.930
in the group--

00:41:00.930 --> 00:41:03.510
starting with one
thought and then kind

00:41:03.510 --> 00:41:05.190
of just rolling
into something else.

00:41:05.190 --> 00:41:10.260
And so that's how the recipes
evolve from those conversations

00:41:10.260 --> 00:41:12.940
and from tasting.

00:41:12.940 --> 00:41:15.790
SPEAKER 2: We'll take
two more questions.

00:41:15.790 --> 00:41:18.469
Yes, go on.

00:41:18.469 --> 00:41:19.010
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:41:19.010 --> 00:41:23.750
I'm not exactly the best cook,
maybe not even very good.

00:41:23.750 --> 00:41:27.800
Have you got any
kitchen cheats or hacks

00:41:27.800 --> 00:41:29.730
that could help my skill level?

00:41:29.730 --> 00:41:31.730
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: First
of all, I want to say,

00:41:31.730 --> 00:41:35.400
before I give you
a bit of advice,

00:41:35.400 --> 00:41:40.490
it's funny how it goes
back to the discussion

00:41:40.490 --> 00:41:42.790
that we had about
cooking at ease.

00:41:42.790 --> 00:41:45.990
There is a real pressure
to be good at everything.

00:41:45.990 --> 00:41:49.010
And cooking is not something
you need to be good at.

00:41:49.010 --> 00:41:51.560
There's so many
good places to eat--

00:41:51.560 --> 00:41:52.856
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:54.110 --> 00:41:56.690
--all around, everywhere.

00:41:56.690 --> 00:42:01.427
I feel that there's this
pressure for everybody to cook.

00:42:01.427 --> 00:42:03.260
And I know a lot of
people that don't really

00:42:03.260 --> 00:42:05.860
love cooking that much, and
it's really not a problem.

00:42:05.860 --> 00:42:08.716
So you're in a safe space.

00:42:08.716 --> 00:42:09.590
It's absolutely fine.

00:42:09.590 --> 00:42:11.926
My sister, when I came
up with this book,

00:42:11.926 --> 00:42:14.300
she said to me, oh, my God,
finally I can cook your food.

00:42:17.930 --> 00:42:21.710
I don't think it's her
number one leisure activity.

00:42:21.710 --> 00:42:22.620
She's got three kids.

00:42:22.620 --> 00:42:27.300
She's got a busy job, a busy
life, and she just didn't cook.

00:42:27.300 --> 00:42:30.790
This book is full
of tricks for you.

00:42:30.790 --> 00:42:33.710
And I think one of those
things I can only say

00:42:33.710 --> 00:42:37.830
is that if you see a
recipe that says to you,

00:42:37.830 --> 00:42:39.650
I want to eat that,
that's step one.

00:42:39.650 --> 00:42:40.650
That's really important.

00:42:40.650 --> 00:42:42.920
And the next step is just
read carefully through

00:42:42.920 --> 00:42:44.920
and see there's nothing
challenging or too

00:42:44.920 --> 00:42:47.300
overcomplicated and try it.

00:42:47.300 --> 00:42:50.450
I think that is the
best way around it.

00:42:50.450 --> 00:42:53.240
There is a dish here,
another pasta dish.

00:42:53.240 --> 00:42:57.950
I think that's a very
good place to start.

00:42:57.950 --> 00:43:03.590
It's got tinned chickpeas,
za'atar, and olive oil.

00:43:03.590 --> 00:43:05.312
And those are all
cupboard ingredients,

00:43:05.312 --> 00:43:07.520
and it's something you can
put together very quickly.

00:43:07.520 --> 00:43:11.250
And you can be really
proud of your achievement

00:43:11.250 --> 00:43:15.170
and not feel that you've cheated
in a very substantial way.

00:43:15.170 --> 00:43:16.830
Because again, it
doesn't matter.

00:43:16.830 --> 00:43:18.920
Because when people taste
it and say it's amazing,

00:43:18.920 --> 00:43:20.753
you don't need to tell
them how easy it was.

00:43:20.753 --> 00:43:21.905
[LAUGHS]

00:43:21.905 --> 00:43:24.274
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:43:24.274 --> 00:43:24.815
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:43:24.815 --> 00:43:25.790
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: Hey.

00:43:25.790 --> 00:43:28.370
AUDIENCE: So what's next
for you for the next one-

00:43:28.370 --> 00:43:31.254
to five-year plan?

00:43:31.254 --> 00:43:32.014
[LAUGHS]

00:43:32.014 --> 00:43:33.680
SPEAKER 2: Googlers
really like actions.

00:43:33.680 --> 00:43:36.830
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI: That is
kind of a long trajectory.

00:43:39.480 --> 00:43:41.530
Well, I don't really know.

00:43:41.530 --> 00:43:43.460
And that's a very
genuine answer,

00:43:43.460 --> 00:43:46.610
because I have never had a plan.

00:43:46.610 --> 00:43:49.540
So there is definitely going
to be a book coming out,

00:43:49.540 --> 00:43:52.070
not next year because
I'm taking a year off,

00:43:52.070 --> 00:43:53.914
because it's been too much.

00:43:53.914 --> 00:43:55.330
But the year after
that, I'm going

00:43:55.330 --> 00:43:56.496
to have another book coming.

00:43:56.496 --> 00:44:02.220
And that book will explore
the notion of flexitarianism

00:44:02.220 --> 00:44:03.870
that I talked about.

00:44:03.870 --> 00:44:07.490
So I don't want to
reveal too much of it.

00:44:07.490 --> 00:44:11.350
But I think a little
bit that you can be--

00:44:11.350 --> 00:44:13.730
and don't quote me on that--

00:44:13.730 --> 00:44:17.120
a vegetarian and you can
still use fish sauce.

00:44:17.120 --> 00:44:18.940
No, probably not.

00:44:18.940 --> 00:44:22.910
But the notion that
you could choose

00:44:22.910 --> 00:44:27.110
that kind of line of
eating and cooking

00:44:27.110 --> 00:44:28.550
is the way I'm exploring now.

00:44:28.550 --> 00:44:30.920
So it's kind of flavor
ideas of flavor bombs

00:44:30.920 --> 00:44:35.480
that could really enhance
your vegetable-focused meal

00:44:35.480 --> 00:44:39.620
and turn them into something
super delicious is what I'm

00:44:39.620 --> 00:44:40.842
thinking about for that book.

00:44:40.842 --> 00:44:42.300
But it's really
just the beginning,

00:44:42.300 --> 00:44:43.716
because I've got
a couple of years

00:44:43.716 --> 00:44:45.390
to work on that-- or
a year and a half.

00:44:45.390 --> 00:44:51.350
And then I don't really
know, I have to be honest.

00:44:51.350 --> 00:44:53.540
I don't think we're going
to open another restaurant

00:44:53.540 --> 00:44:55.550
for at least another
two or three years,

00:44:55.550 --> 00:44:58.890
because restaurants
are a nightmare.

00:44:58.890 --> 00:45:01.340
Even successful restaurants,
behind the scenes,

00:45:01.340 --> 00:45:04.970
are a nightmare, because
it's just really difficult

00:45:04.970 --> 00:45:05.930
to run a restaurant.

00:45:05.930 --> 00:45:08.180
And with Brexit, we
also have less people

00:45:08.180 --> 00:45:12.200
coming through the door to
take the jobs that we need.

00:45:12.200 --> 00:45:14.712
So it's become increasingly
more difficult.

00:45:14.712 --> 00:45:16.170
But the restaurants
are doing well,

00:45:16.170 --> 00:45:18.336
so there probably will be
another one at some point.

00:45:18.336 --> 00:45:21.110
But there isn't one
planned for any time

00:45:21.110 --> 00:45:22.370
in the very near future.

00:45:22.370 --> 00:45:24.320
SPEAKER 2: Will you
expand internationally?

00:45:24.320 --> 00:45:26.960
YOTAM OTTOLENGHI:
Expand internationally?

00:45:26.960 --> 00:45:30.260
This is a conversation that
we've had a lot in the past.

00:45:30.260 --> 00:45:34.760
And the difficulty with
that is that, first of all,

00:45:34.760 --> 00:45:35.790
it's a lifestyle choice.

00:45:35.790 --> 00:45:37.430
So that means
someone needs to be

00:45:37.430 --> 00:45:38.960
going from one
country to the other

00:45:38.960 --> 00:45:41.780
all the time to make
sure it's done properly.

00:45:41.780 --> 00:45:43.232
The other is the
quality control.

00:45:43.232 --> 00:45:44.690
So you need to
partner with someone

00:45:44.690 --> 00:45:47.580
that really understands
the ethos and how it works.

00:45:47.580 --> 00:45:52.010
And I know there's a lot
of chefs that do that.

00:45:52.010 --> 00:45:53.120
Some do it really well.

00:45:53.120 --> 00:45:54.170
Others failed.

00:45:54.170 --> 00:45:56.480
So there's all sorts
of examples of how

00:45:56.480 --> 00:45:59.690
that international
expansion plays out.

00:45:59.690 --> 00:46:03.895
But it's a possibility.

00:46:03.895 --> 00:46:06.620
And like I say, I can't
tell how many conversations

00:46:06.620 --> 00:46:08.630
I've been in when we
discussed that option

00:46:08.630 --> 00:46:11.300
and then dismissed it
on all sorts of grounds.

00:46:11.300 --> 00:46:12.990
So I don't know yet.

00:46:12.990 --> 00:46:14.316
We'll see.

00:46:14.316 --> 00:46:14.975
SPEAKER 2: OK.

00:46:14.975 --> 00:46:16.700
Well, I think we may
have to wrap it up.

00:46:16.700 --> 00:46:18.440
A few closing comments from me--

00:46:20.990 --> 00:46:24.470
Cafe Royal is
celebrating the book,

00:46:24.470 --> 00:46:27.380
and they've cooked at least
a dozen dishes for you

00:46:27.380 --> 00:46:30.290
to try out, which is great.

00:46:30.290 --> 00:46:33.470
Yotam has a podcast, which
is actually really excellent.

00:46:33.470 --> 00:46:35.620
You can find it on Spotify.

00:46:35.620 --> 00:46:38.690
Features guests such
as Lin-Manuel Miranda,

00:46:38.690 --> 00:46:42.080
Nigella Lawson, Nadia Hussain.

00:46:42.080 --> 00:46:44.978
Great to listen to.

00:46:44.978 --> 00:46:50.730
And last but not least,
already a bestselling book,

00:46:50.730 --> 00:46:54.020
so hopefully you
will enjoy the dishes

00:46:54.020 --> 00:46:55.340
and go out and buy the book.

00:46:55.340 --> 00:46:58.880
But can you please
join me in thanking

00:46:58.880 --> 00:47:00.630
Yotam for coming in today?

00:47:00.630 --> 00:47:01.230
Thank you.

00:47:01.230 --> 00:47:03.980
[APPLAUSE]

